The new hope of India
CAMBRIDGE, MASSACHUSETTS – India’s latest election may prove to be the most important positive economic event of 2014.
Indian voters decisively rejected the Congress party, which had ruled India almost uninterrupted since independence in 1947.
They might feel happy about this decision.
Since 1998, Sonia Gandhi, widow of former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and leader of the Congress Party, has been effectively running the show, while Prime Minister Singh is merely a puppet.
Under her leadership, the Congress Party pursued populist agendas, increased transfer payments, leading to India's annual GDP growth rate dropping below 4% in 2013.
Per capita GDP remains around $4,000, which is less than half of China's level.
The newly-elected Prime Minister Narendra Modi had campaigned for the election by promising fast-growing job and income creation across India, as in his home state of Gujarat when he was the chief minister.
Under Modi's leadership, Gujarat became a business-friendly state, expanding economic activities and attracting commercial investments from both within India and abroad.
A key feature of the latest election is that Modi's Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) won an absolute majority in the全国人民代表大会, which can be considered a unprecedented achievement in India.   Note: There seems to be a slight mismatch in the original sentence where "National Parliament" (国民议会) is referred to, but in the context of India, it might likely be the "Lok Sabha" (lower house of the Parliament of India). If you meant to refer to the Lok Sabha, the corrected translation would be:  A key feature of the latest election is that Modi's Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) won an absolute majority in the Lok Sabha, which can be considered a unprecedented achievement in India.
Therefore, Modi does not need to compromise with other national or regional political parties to pursue his legislative agenda.
Two key officials will help Modi with his economic plans.
The newly appointed Finance Minister Arun Jaitley is politically experienced and has held ministerial positions in the previous BJP government.
Jeter is also known as a strategic thinker with sympathetic views on business interests.
Raghuram Rajan will continue to serve as the governor of the Reserve Bank of India (the central bank). Rajan is an outstanding economist who, during his tenure as governor, demonstrated a desire to reduce India’s high double-digit annual inflation rate and attempted to reform some productivity constraints in India’s financial sector.
The measures needed to stimulate economic growth will take time to be implemented and yield results.
But if you want to know whether the new government is taking action to achieve faster long-term growth, you should examine progress in the following ten policy areas.
Education.
Despite India's exceptional higher education and technical institutions, only a small portion of the population can access the opportunities they provide, because elementary and secondary education in India is extremely underdeveloped.
Only 60% of Indian adults have basic literacy skills equivalent to primary education.
The teachers themselves have inadequate educational qualifications and lack work motivation; many teachers do not even show up at their assigned schools.
Infrastructure.
India needs better roads and ports to efficiently transport its products across the country and around the world.
The recent expansion of private air routes and airports indicates that private enterprises can also play a role in this field.
Fiscal integration.
Large budget deficits absorb national savings that should have been used to expand business investment. The budget deficits lead to an increase in national debt that can only be financed by future taxes.
Privatization.
The efficiency of all manufacturing and other industrial enterprises owned by the Indian government is low, often resulting in the depletion of national savings.
Selling these enterprises directly contributes to accelerating economic growth.
The Chinese characters "消补贴" can be translated into English as "Subsidy Cancellation" or "Subsidy Elimination," depending on the context. If you could provide more context, I could give a more precise translation.
Subsidies for electricity and energy lead to wasteful overconsumption and an increase in fiscal deficits.
Despite these subsidies being politically difficult to取消，在这里应该使用"repeal"或者"eliminate"来更准确地传达原句的意思，但是为了保持句子通顺，可以调整为：Despite these subsidies being politically difficult to repeal, they should be replaced with cash transfers. Currently, due to the implementation of a notable fingerprint-based cash transfer system, India's cash transfer efficiency is relatively high.
Agricultural reforms.
Under the current system, the government purchases, stores, and distributes agricultural products.
The result is that large quantities of goods are stockpiled in warehouses, while production incentives are misaligned.
The agricultural market should be privatized.
Property rights and regional demarcation.
If you have been to Mumbai or any other major Indian city, you would see how area-based restrictions lead to inefficient land use in towns, hindering densification.
Unclear property rights, particularly those pertaining to agricultural land, hindered industrialization in rural areas.
Relax foreign investment restrictions.
Currently, foreign enterprises are unable to become controlling shareholders of banks and insurance companies.
Relaxing these restrictions could strengthen the financial sector and play an important role in economic growth.
Tax reform.
The complex system of central and state value-added taxes in India distorts domestic trade.
The debate over replacing these taxes with a nationwide value-added tax and moving to a分税制 (fēn shuì zhì, which refers to a system of fiscal federalism or revenue division between the central and local governments) should now enter the implementation phase.
Corruption.
High-level corruption cases undermine economic confidence and also hinder official decision-making.
India is also plagued by small-scale corruption, with bribery becoming a common feature in all business and personal transactions.
The government should严厉 punish high-level corruption and limit petty corruption through a new system of cash transfer payments.
Driven by stronger growth and expectations of increased profits, Indian stock markets have risen by 20% this year.
Now, Modi and the Bharatiya Janata Party need to prove to the world that they can deliver on their election promises.
